To test the hypothesis that the full-length S gene of BCoV undergoes positive selection, we examined site models and branch site models implemented in the BASEML and CODEML program of the PAML v4.6 package [

 18

]. The substitution rate ratios for non-synonymous (dN) versus synonymous (dS) mutations (Ï) were calculated. The Ï ratio for C1, C2, C3, and Vietnam BCoV strains were 0.15734, 0.11613, 1.90805, and 0.10297, respectively (Table

 1

). Naive empirical Bayes (NEB) analysis identified positively selected sites within the S protein in the C1 cluster as aa 179 and aa 501 (

 p

>â99%), whereas Bayes empirical Bayes analysis identified four aa positions (11, 179, 499, 501, 1352) (

 p

>â99%) (Table

 1

). NEB analysis estimated positively selected sites in the C2 cluster as aa 113, aa 501, and aa 525 (

 p

>â99%) (Table

 1

). Two strong positive selection sites were detected within the receptor-binding subunit of the S protein gene, spanning aa residues 109â131 and aa 497â527 [

 5

]. The selection pattern along the S glycoprotein implies adaptive evolution of BCoVs, suggesting a successful mechanism by which the virus continually circulates among cattle and other ruminants [

 5

].

